{
  "query": "How do the effects of using cutting or mowing to mimic grazing vary between studies in Italy and Spain?",
  "relevant_summary": "Studies in Italy and Spain show contrasting effects when using cutting/mowing to mimic grazing. In Italy, a site comparison study found that mowing increased heather cover and grass cover while reducing tree cover. Another Italian study showed that meadows cut once/year had higher species richness of butterflies and moths compared to meadows cut two or more times/year, and meadows cut occasionally or once/year had higher abundance of pollinators including butterflies than intensively mown grasslands. In contrast, two replicated, randomized, before-and-after trials in Spain (one controlled) found that using cutting to mimic grazing reduced heather cover rather than increasing it. Spanish studies also showed more variable effects on plant species richness - one replicated, randomized, controlled, before-and-after trial found that cutting increased the number of plant species, but another replicated, randomized, before-and-after trial found that the number of plant species only increased in a minority of cases. Both countries showed increased grass cover from cutting, but the effects on overall plant biodiversity and heather cover differed between Italian and Spanish studies.",
